--- title: "STAC Tutorial" description: "Learn how to use the GRASS addon t.stac to search and import STAC API data into a GRASS project." toc: true toc-depth: 4 format: html: code-copy: true code-fold: false code-tools: true execute: enabled: true keep-ipynb: true eval: false freeze: auto cache: true jupyter: python3 author: Corey T. White date: '2025-03-01' categories: [stac, grass-addon, tutorial] page-layout: full title-block-banner: true draft: false --- In this tutorial we will learn about the [t.stac](https://grass.osgeo.org/grass-stable/manuals/addons/t.stac.html) suite of tools for [GRASS](https://grass.osgeo.org). * [t.stac.catalog](https://grass.osgeo.org/grass-stable/manuals/addons/t.stac.catalog.html) - is a tool for exploring SpatioTemporal Asset Catalogs metadata from a STAC API. * [t.stac.collection](https://grass.osgeo.org/grass-stable/manuals/addons/t.stac.collection.html) - is a tool for exploring SpatioTemporal Asset Catalog (STAC) collection metadata. * [t.stac.item](https://grass.osgeo.org/grass-stable/manuals/addons/t.stac.item.html) - is a tool for exploring and importing SpatioTemporal Asset Catalog item metadata and assets into GRASS. ## Introduction SpatioTemporal Asset Catalog (STAC)... The tutorial assumes you already have GRASS installed on your machine. If not please [download and install GRASS](https://grass.osgeo.org/download/) before continuing the tutorial. ## Getting Started ### Start GRASS Session ::: {#config-grass .cell execution_count=2} ``` {.python .cell-code} # Import standard python packages import sys import subprocess from IPython.display import display, JSON, HTML import json import pandas as pd # import polars as pl # Ask GRASS where its Python packages are and add them to the path sys.path.append( subprocess.check_output(["grass", "--config", "python_path"], text=True).strip() ) # Import the GRASS python packages we need import grass.script as gs import grass.jupyter as gj ``` ::: Create a GRASS project ::: {#create-project .cell execution_count=3} ``` {.python .cell-code} gs.create_project("stac", epsg="32119", overwrite=True) ``` ::: and start a GRASS session ::: {#start-grass-session .cell execution_count=4} ``` {.python .cell-code} session = gj.init("stac") ``` ::: ### Install Addon The [t.stac](https://grass.osgeo.org/grass-stable/manuals/addons/t.stac.html) addons require the following Python packages. * [pystac (>=1.12)](https://pystac.readthedocs.io/en/latest/installation.html) * [pystac_client (>=0.8)](https://pystac-client.readthedocs.io/en/stable/) * [tqdm (>=4.67)](https://tqdm.github.io/) You can install them using pip or the Python package manager of your choice. ```bash pip install pystac pystac_client tqdm ``` Now you can install the extensions. ::: {#install-t-stac .cell execution_count=5} ``` {.python .cell-code} gs.run_command("g.extension", extension="t.stac") ``` ::: ## Set computational region ::: {#grass-set-region .cell execution_count=6} ``` {.python .cell-code} gs.run_command( "g.region", n=236687, s=210391, e=616042, w=598921, nsres=10, ewres=10, flags="pa" ) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` projection: 99 (NAD83 / North Carolina) zone: 0 datum: nad83 ellipsoid: grs80 north: 236690 south: 210390 west: 598920 east: 616050 nsres: 10 ewres: 10 rows: 2630 cols: 1713 cells: 4505190 ``` ::: ::: ::: {#cell-display-interactive-region .cell execution_count=7} ``` {.python .cell-code} m = gj.InteractiveMap(use_region=True) display(m.show()) ``` ::: {#display-interactive-region .cell-output .cell-output-display} ```{=html} ``` ::: ::: ## STAC API ::: {#set-stac-catalog-url .cell execution_count=8} ``` {.python .cell-code} stac_url = "https://earth-search.aws.element84.com/v1/" ``` ::: ### Searching STAC Catalogs ::: {#tbl-stac-catalog .cell execution_count=9} ``` {.python .cell-code} catalogs_json = gs.parse_command( "t.stac.catalog", url=stac_url, flags="b", format="json" ) df_catalogs = pd.json_normalize(catalogs_json) display(df_catalogs.head(10)) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display} ```{=html}

``` ::: ::: #### Collection Metadata ::: {#tbl-stac-items .cell execution_count=10} ``` {.python .cell-code} items_json = gs.parse_command( "t.stac.item", url=stac_url, collection_id="sentinel-2-l2a", flags="m", format="json", ) df_items = pd.json_normalize(items_json, max_level=0) display(df_items.T.head(5)) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display} ```{=html}
